  "prompt": "Who are Hindu Gods?",
  "response": "Hinduism, one of the world's oldest religions, has a rich pantheon of deities. Hindu gods are diverse and can be categorized in various ways. Here are some of the principal deities in Hinduism:\n\n1. **Brahma**: The creator god responsible for the creation of the universe and all living beings. He is one part of the Trimurti.\n\n2. **Vishnu**: The preserver and protector of the universe. Vishnu has many avatars, including Rama and Krishna, who descend to Earth to restore cosmic order.\n\n3. **Shiva**: The destroyer and transformer god, also part of the Trimurti. He is often depicted in deep meditation or dancing (Nataraja) to symbolize the cosmic cycles of creation and destruction.\n\n4. **Lakshmi**: The goddess of wealth, fortune, and prosperity, and the consort of Vishnu.\n\n5. **Parvati**: The goddess of love, fertility, and devotion, and the consort of Shiva. She has various forms, including Durga and Kali.\n\n6. **Saraswati**: The goddess of knowledge, music, art, and wisdom.\n\n7. **Ganesha**: The elephant-headed god of wisdom, knowledge, and new beginnings. He is the son of Shiva and Parvati.\n\n8. **Hanuman**: The monkey god, devotee of Lord Rama, symbolizing strength, devotion, and service.\n\n9. **Krishna**: An avatar of Vishnu, revered as the supreme god in some traditions. His teachings in the Bhagavad Gita are fundamental to Hindu philosophy.\n\n10. **Rama**: Another avatar of Vishnu, hero of the Ramayana, and symbol of virtue and righteousness.\n\n11. **Durga**: A warrior goddess who combats evil forces. She is an aspect of Parvati.\n\n12. **Kali**: The fierce goddess of time, death, and change, another aspect of Parvati.\n\n13. **Surya**: The sun god, representing the supreme light and energy.\n\nThere are many regional and lesser-known gods and goddesses, and each has its own significance, stories, and forms of worship within Hinduism\u2019s broad and diverse practices.",
